<Base title="Education" lang="en" description="Hungarian language education at the Szent László Hungarian School in Vancouver.">
  <div class="container container--narrow prose">
    <h1 class="page-title">Education</h1>

    <p>
      We teach the children to read and write using elementary school textbooks from
      Hungary. With the older students we also touch on Hungarian literature and
      grammar, geography, and history during the school year. We place great emphasis
      on introducing Hungarian traditions and holidays as well. Naturally — as in
      every weekend school where classes take place once a week — we cannot follow
      the full curriculum of elementary schools in Hungary.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our goal is for the children to fall in love with the Hungarian language and
      to receive a foundation that turns learning Hungarian into something that comes
      from within — so that they read and study Hungarian on their own at home, too.
      We continuously source our textbooks from Hungary and try to follow the latest
      teaching methods.
    </p>
    <p>
      In recent years, more and more children have come to us who are learning
      Hungarian as a foreign language, since their families speak mostly English at
      home. This is a new challenge in the life of the school, but our teachers are
      open to training and new directions, so we can keep up with what is needed.
      One silver lining of the pandemic is that classes were held online for two
      years, which made it possible for children living in the wider Vancouver area
      to join as well.
    </p>
    <p>
      We want to show young and old alike, in a playful way, how wonderful the
      Hungarian language is — and thereby open a new path for them in the world.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
